WEBVTT

00:00:00.220 --> 00:00:05.290
Let’s explore the interpolation feature, a central component of PyAnalySeries

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.270
Thanks to the application’s interactivity, defining an interpolation becomes a

00:00:10.270 --> 00:00:12.730
simple and intuitive process!

00:00:12.730 --> 00:00:14.910
Let’s consider a real use case.

00:00:14.910 --> 00:00:18.640
The example files are available in the installation directory.

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:21.120
First, open the files.

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:24.780
You can load multiple files, referred to as WorkSheets in

00:00:24.780 --> 00:00:26.420
the application.

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:28.540
The format is based on the open.

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:30.520
xlsx standard.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:33.350
Open the two files as shown in the video.

00:00:34.630 --> 00:00:38.330
Now select the variables to interpolate, along with their reference

00:00:38.330 --> 00:00:42.810
series — here, delta C 13 and delta O 18

00:00:43.770 --> 00:00:46.980
Use the Control key to select multiple series.

00:00:46.980 --> 00:00:49.700
The selection order does not matter, but for clarity, we

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:51.350
will choose the reference first.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:55.610
Open the interpolation window.

00:00:55.610 --> 00:01:00.470
In practice, this consists of identifying correspondences between two series

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:03.520
This is where interactivity becomes essential.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:07.240
You can place tie points either on transitions or directly

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:08.320
on data points.

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:12.880
We now have four series selected.

00:01:13.950 --> 00:01:16.660
Start with delta O 18.

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:19.690
Define the reference and the series to interpolate using the

00:01:19.690 --> 00:01:21.120
selection controls.

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:26.200
Identify similar transition zones.

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:32.030
Hold Shift and click to place the vertical dashed line

00:01:32.030 --> 00:01:33.550
in each window.

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:35.220
Then press C to connect them.

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:40.180
This creates a pair of corresponding points — called pointers

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:45.090
Select another transition and repeat the operation.

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:52.100
Once two pairs are defined, the interpolation appears automatically.

00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:55.460
Press Z, or enable “ Show interpolated curve ”, to

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:56.840
toggle its display.

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:03.360
You can also compare interpolation methods — linear or polynomial

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:05.360
— and observe their effect.

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:11.110
Now refine the interpolation by placing a pointer directly on

00:02:11.110 --> 00:02:12.570
a data point.

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:14.730
Hold Control and click on the point.

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:18.140
Repeat this on the reference series, then connect the two

00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:18.980
pointers.

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:25.280
In short: Shift-click places a free pointer.

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:27.750
Control-click snaps to a data point.

00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:34.200
To undo the last connection, click “ Remove last connection

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:35.120
” or press U.

00:02:36.230 --> 00:02:39.940
To delete a specific connection, hover over it — it

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:42.450
turns red — then press X.

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:46.870
Press uppercase X to remove all pointers.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:51.770
You can review all pointer values in the “ Pointers

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:52.270
” tab.

00:02:53.430 --> 00:02:56.320
In the “ Pointers plot ” tab, you can visualize

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:59.870
X2 as a function of X1, along with the gradient

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:04.410
If X2 is time and X1 is depth, this gradient

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:06.390
represents the sedimentation rate.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:11.700
During the process, you may need to switch variables to

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:12.990
refine the alignment.

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:17.020
Switch to delta C 13.

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:20.070
Define a new correspondence and connect the points.

00:03:22.270 --> 00:03:25.710
Then switch back to delta O 18.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:32.710
This iterative workflow allows you to progressively improve the interpolation

00:03:35.210 --> 00:03:37.860
Let’s now look at the result produced by an experienced

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:38.680
user.

00:03:43.050 --> 00:03:47.230
Once satisfied, you can save either the interpolation or the

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:50.180
interpolation and the current interpolated series.

00:03:52.420 --> 00:03:55.920
You can also load an existing pointer file to refine

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:57.690
or adjust your interpolation.

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.220
In the next step, we will see how to apply

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:04.670
this interpolation to a set of series.
